            ">The invisible giant</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           Just after the American Civil War, William Wallace Cargill saw that America was hungry. He realized the future lay not just in growing grain, but in storing, and he understood that railroads would be the backbone of agriculture. Realizing this, Cargill set up a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-1-1-grain-warehouse?source=website" target="_blank">grain warehouse</a> right next to the tracks, cutting down transportation expense and time drastically. His simple yet brilliant strategy gave Cargill a huge competitive edge just as the US Midwest became the world’s breadbasket.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/cargill-salmonir-omega3-spectroscopy-tech.jpg" alt="Cargill’s SalmoNIR technology uses near-infrared spectroscopy to provide salmon farmers with real-time data on things like omega-3 fatty acids" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i> 
             Cargill’s SalmoNIR technology uses near-infrared spectroscopy to provide salmon farmers with real-time data on things like omega-3 fatty acids. Credits: Cargill</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         From there, he partnered with his brothers and built a network of grain elevators that made Cargill the indispensable middleman between farmers and markets. By controlling storage and logistics, they shaped and controlled the flow of global agriculture. The next generation expanded beyond grain into cotton, meat, and anything moving across borders that was profitable and always in demand. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Cargill distributes a wide range of products, including corn syrup, meat, and cosmetics. While many competitors went public, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-1-2-cargill-remained-private?source=website" target="_blank">Cargill remained private</a>. By the 1980s, they were the largest privately held company in America, and arguably still are. The company remains 89% family-owned with over 100 family members as shareholders. </p>
        </mj-text>
