            ">The politics of Koch </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          Fred C. Koch was an MIT-trained chemical genius who, back in 1927, cracked the code on turning <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-2-3-heavy-crude-oil-into-gasoline?source=website" target="_blank">heavy crude oil into gasoline</a> cheaper and faster. The oil giants saw him as a risk to their businesses and sued him out of the American market. So Fred went international, building oil refineries in the Soviet Union, Germany, and the Middle East during the 1930s. He helped both Stalin and Hitler industrialize. </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/koch-brothers-political-strategy-wealth.jpg" alt="The Koch brothers have been strategically reshaping politics and amassing a fortune that would power their chosen strategy" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>The Koch brothers have been strategically reshaping politics and amassing a fortune that would power their chosen strategy. Credits: Wichita Eagle</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          In 1940, Fred Koch founded Wood River Oil and Refining, later known as Koch Industries. After his death in 1967, his son Charles transformed it into a diversified industrial empire using his Market-Based Management philosophy. By mastering risk, trading, and internal operations, Koch grew into a refining giant. The <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-2-4-2025-acquisition-of-georgia-pacific?source=website" target="_blank">2005 acquisition of Georgia-Pacific</a> expanded it into consumer products, stabilizing revenue. </p> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          Charles Koch still leads after 50 years, with a $100B+ family fortune, and his son Chase is focused on tech and venture investments. But Koch held its supremacy not just through its business acumen but also by making itself a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-2-5-political-heavyweight-in-the-us?source=website" target="_blank">political heavyweight in the US</a>. Their vast political network enables them to influence legislation, secure government contracts, and obtain permits more quickly and favorably than their competitors. </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The oil monarchy</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
         Back in the early 1930s, oil was discovered in the Arabian Peninsula, not by locals, but by an American company called the California Arabian Standard Oil Company, currently known as Aramco. For decades, Aramco was basically an American-owned enterprise, pumping and exporting Saudi oil. Meanwhile, the Saudi royal family, the Al Saud, was quietly plotting to take back control. </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/aramco-global-expansion-1990s-partnerships.jpg" alt="Throughout the 1990s, Aramco gradually extended its ties and partnerships across the world" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Throughout the 1990s, Aramco gradually extended its ties and partnerships across the world. Credits: Aramco</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Recognizing oil’s value, the Saudi government started pushing back in the 1950s. They raised taxes and royalties, demanded more Saudi nationals to be employed, and insisted on infrastructure and state institutions funded by oil revenues. By the 1980s, these efforts culminated in the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-09-08-2025-3-6-full-nationalization-of-aramco?source=website" target="_blank">full nationalization of Aramco</a>. They bought out the American shareholders and had complete control. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
        Aramco is more than an ordinary family business. It's a strategic power tool of the Saudi monarchy. Controlling Aramco means controlling the oil that funds their rule, government, and global influence, elevating them far beyond a typical monarchy. While the company went partially public in 2019, the Al Saud family still holds majority control. Beyond oil, Aramco has expanded into refining, petrochemicals, and global energy trading, transforming into a full-spectrum energy empire. </p>
        </mj-text>
